      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA implementations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under documented software quality plans. Version control, regression testing, and release validation records are available for each solver environment. Required and achieved levels are commensurate with Model Risk Level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark problems with analytical solutions were used to verify the linear static FEA solvers. Patch tests and single-element checks confirm correct element formulation. Results are consistent across the three independent implementations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were performed for the pedicle screw and rod geometry. A Richardson extrapolation-based grid convergence index (GCI) was computed; peak von Mises stress and construct stiffness quantities of interest converged to within 2% between the medium and fine mesh densities used in production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solvers with iterative refinement were employed. Residual norms were confirmed below 1e-8 for all load steps. No ill-conditioning was detected in the assembled stiffness matrices for the construct configurations studied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Standard operating procedures and documented model setup checklists were followed by each of the three analyst teams. Cross-team blind replication confirmed consistent boundary condition application, material assignment, and contact definition. Discrepancies were resolved through documented reconciliation meetings."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic continuum FEA with frictional contact interfaces is judged appropriate for the sub-yield loading regime of the ASTM F1717 protocol. Titanium alloy material behavior is well within the linear range at the applied load levels. Model form uncertainty is bounded by the multi-team replication exercise."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, Poisson's ratio) were sourced from ASTM F136 certified material test reports for the specific Ti-6Al-4V alloy lot used in the experimental constructs. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual screw and rod hardware."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories, providing replicate measurements for statistical comparison. Sample provenance, lot traceability, and pre-test dimensional inspection records are archived."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single load condition (compression-bending at the ASTM F1717 specified angle and offset). Variation across load magnitudes or alternative orientations was not explored. This single test condition limits the achieved level to 2, falling below the required level of 3 for Model Risk Level 3. This gap is acknowledged as a limitation of the current validation dataset."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "A systematic parameter mapping was performed to confirm that FEA boundary conditions, loading fixtures, and interface conditions faithfully represent the physical test setup. Contact preloads from screw torque were estimated and applied consistently. Fixture compliance was characterized and incorporated."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and peak displacement at a defined load level were compared between FEA predictions and experimental measurements using mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) and a validation metric based on the area validation metric. All three FEA implementations fell within the experimental variability band for the primary quantity of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and displacement under ASTM F1717 loading are directly relevant to the regulatory submission question of mechanical performance adequacy. These quantities are the same outputs used in predicate device comparisons and are traceable to the intended decision context."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for the declared model risk.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities directly replicate the physical test protocol (ASTM F1717) and geometry (non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw) corresponding to the device under assessment. The experimental corpus spans two laboratories, supporting generalizability of the validation evidence to the intended use."
    }
  ],
